# 19. Linux Networking Commands for SRE

Check network interfaces.

```bash
ip a
```

Shows all network interfaces and IP addresses.

---

Check routing table.

```bash
ip route
```

Displays routing paths used by the system.

---

Check open ports.

```bash
ss -lntp
```

Shows listening TCP ports and associated processes.

---

View active connections.

```bash
netstat -tulpn
```

Displays open connections and listening ports.

---

Test connectivity.

```bash
ping host
```

Tests reachability and latency.

---

Trace packet path.

```bash
traceroute host
```

Shows network path between source and destination.

---

DNS lookup.

```bash
dig google.com
```

Queries DNS servers and shows resolution details.

---

# 20. Network Troubleshooting for SRE

Most production incidents involve networking.

Common problems include:

* DNS failures
* packet loss
* firewall blocking traffic
* routing issues
* load balancer misconfiguration

---

## DNS Resolution Failure

Check resolver configuration.

```bash
cat /etc/resolv.conf
```

Test DNS server.

```bash
dig domain.com
```

---

## Port Not Reachable

Check listening services.

```bash
ss -lntp
```

Check firewall rules.

```bash
iptables -L
```

---

## Packet Loss

Test connectivity.

```bash
ping host
```

Trace packet path.

```bash
traceroute host
```

Use advanced diagnostics.

```bash
mtr host
```

---

## High Latency

Possible causes:

* network congestion
* routing issues
* DNS delays
* overloaded servers

Tools used:

ping
traceroute
mtr

